IRS990.ActivityOrMissionDesc: THE WISCONSIN HUMANITIES COUNCIL AWARDS GRANTS TO SUPPORT PROGRAMS IN LIBRARIES, MUSEUMS, UNIVERSITIES, HISTORICAL SOCIETIES, SCHOOLS, AND OTHER NONPROFIT SETTINGS THROUGHOUT THE STATE. THE WISCONSIN HUMANITIES COUNCIL ALSO CREATES PROGRAMS, PARTNERSHIPS, AND PUBLICATIONS TO FULFILL ITS MISSION. THESE PROGRAMS INCLUDE THE WORKING LIVES PROJECT AND A PERIODIC PUBLICATION CALLED "ON."
IRS990.MissionDesc: THE WISCONSIN HUMANITIES COUNCIL SUPPORTS AND CREATES PROGRAMS THAT USE HISTORY, CULTURE, AND DISCUSSION TO STRENGHTEN COMMUNITY LIFE FOR EVERYONE IN WISCONSIN.
IRS990.Desc: THE WISCONSIN HUMANITIES COUNCIL'S GRANT PROGRAM PROVIDES SUPPORT FOR PUBLIC HUMANITIES PROGRAMS THAT ENCOURAGE PARTICIPANTS TO CONVERSE, CONNECT, AND REFLECT UPON OUR WORLD. FROM COMMUNITY DISCUSSION PROGRAMS TO MEDIA PROJECTS, FROM MUSEUM EXHIBITIONS TO PROFESSIONAL DEVELOPMENT FOR EDUCATORS, WHC GRANTS STRENGTHEN COMMUNITIES AND ENRICH THE CULTURAL LIFE OF THE STATE. FOR THIS TAX YEAR, 51 NEW GRANTS WERE AWARDED. THERE WERE APPROXIMATELY 759 GRANT-RELATED EVENTS FUNDED, WITH A TOTAL ATTENDANCE FIGURE OVER 65,000 FOR THIS PAST YEAR.

ProgSrvcAccomActy2Grp.Desc: THE WORKING LIVES PROJECT IS CATALYZING AND ENRICHING DISCUSSION ABOUT WORK ACROSS WISCONSIN. THROUGH PUBLIC EVENTS, RADIO PROGRAMS, EXHIBITS, AND ONLINE RESOURCES, THE PROJECT PROMOTES REFLECTION AND ACTION ABOUT WHAT WORK MEANS FOR EACH OF US, AND FOR ALL OF US TOGETHER. THE SHOPTALK SPEAKER'S SERIES CONTINUED IN 2018 WITH 63 EVENTS WITH ATTENDANCE OVER 2,800. IN ADDITION, WORKING LIVES STAFF PARTNERED WITH THE WISCONSIN BOOK FESTIVAL IN MADISON, AND EX FABULA IN MILWAUKEE FOR ADDITIONAL WORKING LIVES THEMED EVENTS, WITH OVER 300 PEOPLE ATTENDING. WORKING LIVES PROGRAMMING ALSO INCLUDED ONLINE DIGITAL STORYTELLING, IN PARTNERSHIP WITH LOVE WISCONSIN, WITH TOTAL PAGE VIEWS OVER 100,000.

ProgSrvcAccomActy3Grp.Desc: "BEYOND THE HEADLINES" IS A PROGRAM THAT BRINGS MEMBERS OF THE WISCONSIN MEDIA AND THE PUBLIC TOGETHER TO EXAMINE HOW WE CAN OBTAIN INFORMATION THAT WE NEED AND TRUST IN ORDER TO MEET COMMUNITY CHALLENGES. THIS PROJECT WILL BRING WISCONSINITES TOGETHER IN FOUR CITIES FOR DISCUSSIONS THAT EXPLORE JOURNALISM'S CRUCIAL ROLE IN ENABLING CITIZENS TO ENGAGE PRODUCTIVELY IN AMERICAN DEMOCRACY. IN EACH CITY THE WHC WILL USE A DIFFERENT PUBLIC POLICY ISSUE AS A LENS THROUGH WHICH CITIZENS DISCUSS THE PAST, PRESENT, AND FUTURE ROLE OF THE MEDIA IN MEETING THEIR INFORMATION NEEDS. 27 EVENTS HAVE TAKEN PLACE IN WAUSAU, EAU CLAIRE AND MADISON WITH TOTAL ATTENDANCE OVER 500 IN THE CURRENT TAX YEAR, WITH ADDITIONAL PROGRAMING SCHEDULED TO TAKE PLACE NEXT YEAR IN SUPERIOR.

ProgSrvcAccomActyOtherGrp.Desc: IN ADDITION TO ITS OWN PROGRAMMING, THE WHC PROVIDES FINANCIAL SUPPORT OUTSIDE OF THE GRANT PROGRAM FOR HUMANITIES PROGRAMING BY PARTNER ORGANIZATIONS IN THE STATE OF WISCONSIN. THIS YEAR THE WHC CONTINUED ITS PARTNERSHIP WITH WISCONSIN PUBLIC RADIO AND "WISCONSIN LIFE" RADIO PROGRAMMING, AIRING RADIO ESSAYS THAT CELEBRATE WHAT MAKES WISCONSIN UNIQUE THROUGH THE DIVERSE STORIES OF ITS PEOPLE, WITH APPROXIMATELY 70,000 RADIO LISTENERS PER WEEK. THE WHC ALSO CONTINUED ITS SUPPORT OF THE WISCONSIN POET LAUREATE COMMISSION AND THE WISCONSIN POET LAURATE, THE STATE'S AMBASSADOR FOR POETRY. THE WHC IS ONE OF SIX MEMBER ORGANIZATIONS THAT PROVIDE FINANCIAL SUPPORT AND REPRESENTATIVES TO SERVE ON THE POET LAURATE COMMISSION. THE WHC ALSO PARTNERED WITH LOVE WISCONSIN TO CREATE A DIGITAL STORYTELLING PROJECT FOCUSED PRIMARILY ON FACEBOOK, USING THE FACEBOOK GROUPS PLATFORM. DOZENS OF STORIES WERE SHARED AND NUMEROUS DIGITAL CONVERSATIONS BEGAN THIS YEAR, INVOLVING 100'S OF PARTICIPANTS, WITH TOTAL DIGITAL VIEWS SURPASSING 150,000.

THESE GRANT FUNDS ARE AWARDED TO ORGANIZATIONS SERVING ASHLAND, BARON, BAYFIELD, BURNETT, DOUGLASS, FLORENCE, FOREST, IRON, LINCOLN, MARINETTE, ONEIDA, POLK, PRICE, RUSK, SAWYER, VILAS AND WASHBURN COUNTIES. FUNDING DECISIONS FOR THESE GRANT FUNDS PRIORITIZE PROJECTS THAT USE THE HUMANITIES TO ADDRESS ISSUES OF RACE AND ETHNICITY IN WISCONSIN. THESE FUNDS ARE MADE POSSIBLE THANKS TO A GRANT FROM THE MARY HELLEN RICE FOUNDATION.

THESE GRANT FUNDS ARE AWARDED TO ORGANIZATIONS SERVING OCONTO, BROWN AND KEWAUNEE COUNTIES FOR PUBLIC HUMANITIES PROGRAMMING THAT WILL TAKE PLACE IN THOSE COUNTIES. THESE PUBLIC HUMANITIES PROGRAMS, SUCH AS ORAL HISTORY PROJECTS, CURRICULUM DEVELOPMENT, MUSEUM EXHIBITS, BOOK DISCUSSIONS, LECTURE SERIES, GUIDED TOURS, CHILDREN'S PROGRAMS, COMMUNITY FESTIVALS, CIVIC DIALOGUES, OR ANY PROJECT THAT EXPLORES A TOPIC FROM THE PERSPECTIVE OF ONE OR MORE HUMANITIES DISCIPLINES THAT HELP PARTICIPANTS LEARN ABOUT AND REFLECT TOGETHER ON THE THINGS THAT MATTER TO US AS INDIVIDUALS, FAMILIES, AND COMMUNITIES. THIS GRANT POOL IS SUPPORTED BY DONATIONS FROM GREEN BAY AREA DONORS.

SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: THE ORGANIZATION'S LOBBYING ACTIVITIES CONSIST OF ADVOCATING TO LEGISLATORS FOR INCREASED SUPPORT OF HUMANITIES PROGRAMMING IN WISCONSIN.

THE PURPOSE OF THE FUND, SET UP WITH THE UW-FOUNDATION IN SEPTEMBER OF 2002, IS TO SUPPORT WHC-FUNDED PROGRAMMING THAT SERVES CHILDREN AND FAMILIES ACROSS WISCONSIN, WITH PRIORITY GIVEN TO PROGRAMMING THAT SERVES NORTHERN WISCONSIN. INTEREST INCOME FROM THIS ENDOWMENT IS TO BE USED EXCLUSIVELY ON THESE TYPES OF PROJECTS AND PROGRAMMING.

SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: THE WISCONSIN HUMANITIES COUNCIL ARRANGES FOR AN EVALUATION OF MANY MAJOR GRANTS AND SELECTED MINI-GRANTS. THESE EVALUATIONS ARE CONDUCTED BY THE ORGANIZATION'S STAFF, MEMBERS OF THE GOVERNING BODY, OR OUTSIDE EVALUATORS. STAFF MAY SHARE THE RESULTS OF THIS EVALUATION WITH THE PROJECT DIRECTOR AND WITH THE DIRECTORS. GRANT RECIPIENTS ARE ASKED TO SEND A FINAL FINANCIAL AND PROGRAM REPORT TO THE ORGANIZATION WITHIN 90 DAYS OF THE END OF THE PROJECT PERIOD. FOR THE PROGRAM REPORT, THE ORGANIZATION REQUESTS A SUMMARY OF ANY INFORMATION OBTAINED THROUGH AUDIENCE QUESTIONNAIRES, ANY SIGNIFICANT WRITTEN COMMENTS RECEIVED FROM PARTICIPANTS, AND COPIES OF ANY PRESS COVERAGE THAT THE PROJECT RECEIVED.
TO FURTHER OUR CURRENT MISSION, THE WHC STARTED A NEW PROGRAM CALLED BEYOND THE HEADLINES. A DETAILED DESCRIPTION OF THE PROGRAM IS PROVIDED IN LINE 4C.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: FORM 990, PART VI, SECTION A, LINE 3
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: THE ORGANIZATION'S EXECUTIVE DIRECTOR AND ASSOCIATE DIRECTOR ARE EMPLOYEES OF THE UNIVERSITY OF WISCONSIN-EXTENSION AND PERFORM MANAGEMENT DUTIES SUCH AS SUPERVISING PERSONNEL, PLANNING AND EXECUTING BUDGETS AND FINANCIAL OPERATIONS, AND SUPERVISING EXEMPT OPERATIONS. DURING CALENDAR YEAR 2017 THE EXECUTIVE DIRECTOR RECEIVED $86,608 OF REPORTABLE COMPENSATION AND $42,777 OF OTHER COMPENSATION AND THE ASSOCIATE DIRECTOR RECEIVED $64,958 OF REPORTABLE COMPENSATION AND $32,084 OF OTHER COMPENSATION FROM THE UNIVERSITY OF WISCONSIN-EXTENSION.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: FORM 990, PART VI, SECTION B, LINE 11B
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: THE PREPARED FORM 990 IS REVIEWED AND APPROVED BY THE ASSOCIATE DIRECTOR BEFORE THE RETURN IS FILED WITH THE IRS.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: FORM 990, PART VI, SECTION B, LINE 12C
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: THE ORGANIZATION'S CONFLICT OF INTEREST POLICY COVERS ALL OF ITS DIRECTORS AND OFFICERS. ANY DIRECTOR OR OFFICER IS CONSIDERED AN INTERESTED PERSON UNDER THE POLICY. IN CONNECTION WITH ANY ACTUAL OR POSSIBLE CONFLICT OF INTEREST, AN INTERESTED PERSON MUST DISCLOSE THE EXISTENCE OF THE FINANCIAL INTEREST AND BE GIVEN THE OPPORTUNITY TO DISCLOSE ALL MATERIAL FACTS TO THE DIRECTORS CONSIDERING THE PROPOSED TRANSACTION OR ARRANGEMENT. THE INTERESTED PERSON MUST LEAVE THE MEETING OF THE GOVERNING BODY WHILE THE DETERMINATION OF A CONFLICT OF INTEREST IS MADE. THE REMAINING DIRECTORS WILL DECIDE IF A CONFLICT OF INTEREST EXISTS AND WILL VOTE ON THE PROPOSED TRANSACTION OR ARRANGEMENT. THE ORGANIZATION'S DIRECTORS AND OFFICERS DO NOT RECEIVE ANY COMPENSATION ON PROJECTS FUNDED BY THE ORGANIZATION AND MUST RECUSE THEMSELVES FROM THE DELIBERATIONS AND DECISIONS ON GRANT REQUESTS FROM ORGANIZATIONS WITH WHICH THEY ARE AFFILIATED.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: FORM 990, PART VI, SECTION B, LINE 15A
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: THE PERSONNEL COMMITTEE OF THE GOVERNING BODY ANNUALLY EVALUATES THE PERFORMANCE OF THE EXECUTIVE DIRECTOR AND SUBMITS A WRITTEN EVALUATION THAT INCLUDES A COMPENSATION RECOMMENDATION TO THE EXECUTIVE COMMITTEE PRIOR TO THE JUNE COUNCIL MEETING. THE EXECUTIVE DIRECTOR MAY CONFER WITH THE GOVERNING BODY BUT IS ULTIMATELY RESPONSIBLE FOR EVALUATING THE PERFORMANCE OF AND ESTABLISHING COMPENSATION FOR THE REST OF THE ORGANIZATION'S PERSONNEL USING CLEARLY ESTABLISHED POLICIES OUTLINED BY THE UNIVERSITY OF WISCONSIN SYSTEM, OF WHICH THE ORGANIZATION IS ADMINISTRATIVELY AFFILIATED.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: FORM 990, PART VI, SECTION C, LINE 19
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: THE ORGANIZATION MADE ITS GOVERNING DOCUMENTS, CONFLICT OF INTEREST POLICY, AND FINANCIAL STATEMENTS AVAILABLE TO THE PUBLIC UPON REQUEST.
